mean <- dataset%>%
  summarise(mean_BMI = mean(BMI), 
            .by = Year)
ggplot(mean, aes(x = Year, y = mean_BMI))+
  geom_line()
```

From the plot the it is suggested that there is no significant trend followed by the observation over 2008-2012

```{r}
fit_year <- lm(BMI ~ Year,data = df)

library(knitr)
library(broom)

coef_table <- tidy(fit_year)

year_coef <- coef_table[coef_table$term == "Year", ]

# ANOVA
anova_res <- anova(fit_year)

result <- data.frame(
  Term = "Year",
  Estimate = round(year_coef$estimate, 4),
  F_statistic = round(anova_res$`F value`[1], 2),
  P_value = ifelse(anova_res$`Pr(>F)`[1] < 0.001,
                   "<0.001",
                   signif(anova_res$`Pr(>F)`[1], 3))
)

kable(result,
      caption = "Linear Trend of BMI over Time",
      col.names = c("Term", "Estimate", "F", "P-value"),
      booktabs = TRUE)
```

The estimated coefficient for year is small and not statistically significant, suggesting that BMI did not change systematically over time during the study period.
Also the confidence interval is calculated to be [-0.03,0.07] which includes 0 therefore this further suggestes that there is no change in the BMI recorded in Scotland across 2008-2012. 


